WEBVTT

00:01.101 --> 00:02.033
[lively jazz music]

00:02.069 --> 00:03.569
<i> - Adult mark (vo):</i>
<i> Families on tv</i>

00:03.704 --> 00:05.170
<i> Eat at the table.</i>

00:05.206 --> 00:06.638
- Supper!

00:06.640 --> 00:08.673
<i> - I usually ate</i>
<i> in front of the tv</i>

00:08.709 --> 00:10.875
<i> Watching those families</i>
<i> on tv eat.</i>

00:10.911 --> 00:13.111
- Here.
- What is it?

00:13.147 --> 00:14.612
- Food.
Eat it!

00:15.683 --> 00:17.148
<i> - Dad liked to eat</i>
<i> at the kitchen table</i>

00:17.184 --> 00:19.117
<i> So he wouldn't miss himself</i>
<i> on the radio.</i>

00:19.153 --> 00:20.986
- Eat this now
while it's hot.

00:21.121 --> 00:24.122
- Be quiet, will ya?
I can't hear myself speak.

00:24.158 --> 00:26.658
<i> - Mike preferred to eat</i>
<i> in his room alone</i>

00:26.727 --> 00:29.060
<i> Like a wounded wild animal</i>
<i> hiding from predators.</i>

00:29.096 --> 00:31.830
- Mom, get out of my room!
And knock first!

00:31.899 --> 00:33.532
- I don't want to know what
you're doing in here,

00:33.601 --> 00:35.200
Believe me.

00:35.236 --> 00:36.668
[rock music]

00:37.705 --> 00:39.104
<i> - Pop rarely made it</i>
<i> to suppertime.</i>

00:39.173 --> 00:40.672
[pop groans]

00:40.808 --> 00:44.109
<i> My mother never stopped moving</i>
<i> long enough to eat anything.</i>

00:44.111 --> 00:45.744
<i> Food was</i>
<i> for survival</i>

00:45.879 --> 00:47.846
<i> And not something</i>
<i> meant to be enjoyed.</i>

00:47.915 --> 00:49.681
[mumbling]

00:49.817 --> 00:51.483
- What's wrong, mike,
are you choking?

00:51.618 --> 00:53.151
- Pop:
Choking on what?

00:53.220 --> 00:55.087
That food was
boiled to death.

00:55.089 --> 00:56.488
Ask him
if he's drowning.

00:57.424 --> 00:59.258
- Will you
turn on the news?

00:59.393 --> 01:01.192
The cucumbers!
The cucumbers are ready!

01:03.630 --> 01:05.731
<i> - After 500 years</i>
<i> of cod fish,</i>

01:05.733 --> 01:08.867
<i>The government felt it was time</i>
<i>to modernize their economy.</i>

01:08.869 --> 01:10.702
<i> And nothing says</i>
<i> modern like...</i>

01:10.738 --> 01:12.137
<i> - Tv reporter:</i>
<i> Cucumbers.</i>

01:12.272 --> 01:14.206
<i> That's right,</i>
<i> cucumbers.</i>

01:14.341 --> 01:16.041
<i> Premier peckford</i>
<i> announced today</i>

01:16.176 --> 01:18.243
<i> That the government-funded</i>
<i> sprung greenhouse</i>

01:18.245 --> 01:19.845
<i> Has produced the province's</i>
<i> first batch</i>

01:19.914 --> 01:21.513
<i> Of hydroponically-grown</i>
<i> cucumbers.</i>

01:21.648 --> 01:24.215
<i> Thanks to new technology,</i>
<i> they can now take a cucumber</i>

01:24.251 --> 01:27.085
<i> From seedling to grocery aisle</i>
<i> in just six days.</i>

01:27.220 --> 01:29.521
<i> The premier says it's</i>
<i> the start of the green economy</i>

01:29.590 --> 01:32.491
<i> And that $22 million</i>
<i> is a small price to pay</i>

01:32.626 --> 01:34.159
<i> For prosperity.</i>

01:34.161 --> 01:36.461
<i> - News anchor:</i>
<i> That's our own melissa stoke--</i>

01:36.464 --> 01:37.930
- Remember this day.

01:37.932 --> 01:39.598
The day newfoundland
turned the corner.

01:39.600 --> 01:42.334
We are officially
a cucumber province.

01:42.336 --> 01:43.802
- Are you cracked?

01:43.937 --> 01:45.337
Nobody here
likes cucumbers.

01:45.406 --> 01:46.505
- I do.

01:46.640 --> 01:48.640
That greenhouse
is buying advertising time

01:48.676 --> 01:50.775
On the station so,
from now on,

01:50.811 --> 01:53.078
This is a cucumber house!

01:53.147 --> 01:55.280
- You can't grow
anything here.

01:55.349 --> 01:57.549
Newfoundland is a rock.

01:57.585 --> 02:00.085
The soil is as deep
and fertile

02:00.087 --> 02:02.154
As that stuff
in a cat's litter box.

02:02.289 --> 02:03.421
- What's a cucumber?

02:03.457 --> 02:05.357
- It's a fruit.
- It's a vegetable.

02:05.359 --> 02:07.425
- It's a dry pickle.

02:07.495 --> 02:09.294
- They'll never catch on.

02:09.330 --> 02:11.563
I get my greens
second-hand.

02:11.599 --> 02:13.231
Rabbit eats
the lettuce.

02:13.267 --> 02:14.633
I eat the rabbit.

02:14.702 --> 02:17.402
- Imagine all the things
you could grow hydroponically.

02:17.471 --> 02:19.037
Non-traditional crops.

02:19.039 --> 02:21.106
<i> - This wasn't really</i>
<i> news to my brother</i>

02:21.108 --> 02:22.907
<i> Who had already been</i>
<i> experimenting</i>

02:22.943 --> 02:24.509
<i> With his own</i>
<i> non-traditional crops.</i>

02:24.512 --> 02:25.911
<i> [psychedelic music]</i>

02:26.914 --> 02:28.714
- Imagine the
spin-off industries:

02:28.716 --> 02:30.916
Cucumber salads,
pickles,

02:30.985 --> 02:34.986
Some hollywood starlets even put
cucumber slices on their eyes!

02:35.055 --> 02:38.122
- You think you're going to sell
cucumbers to californians?

02:38.159 --> 02:40.058
That's like them
selling us fog.

02:40.060 --> 02:42.060
- We could ship them frozen.

02:42.129 --> 02:44.129
I-I prefer my vegetables
that way

02:44.131 --> 02:45.664
Like peas
or french fries.

02:45.733 --> 02:48.266
- Well, you can worry about
things you're never gonna eat

02:48.335 --> 02:51.403
After you eat what you got
on your bloody plates.

02:51.405 --> 02:52.837
♪♪

02:54.041 --> 02:55.473
[pop groans]

02:57.678 --> 03:00.812
<i> - The next day, cucumber-mania</i>
<i> was rampant at school.</i>

03:00.814 --> 03:02.147
- Did you know

03:02.216 --> 03:04.750
That cucumbers
are 95% water?

03:04.752 --> 03:06.952
- Nobody here
eats cucumbers, sister.

03:07.021 --> 03:08.353
- Well, I will
have you know,

03:08.389 --> 03:09.821
On average,

03:09.823 --> 03:13.091
A newfoundlander eats
a half a cucumber every year.

03:13.160 --> 03:15.827
That's about
250,000 cucumbers.

03:17.097 --> 03:19.831
- And how much is a cucumber
at the supermarket now?

03:19.967 --> 03:21.700
- Well, I don't
buy them myself

03:21.769 --> 03:23.902
But it says here
that they cost

03:24.037 --> 03:25.437
50 cents.

03:25.572 --> 03:29.641
- And how much does one of them
freak cucumbers cost to grow?

03:29.776 --> 03:31.577
- Uh, $27.50.

03:32.680 --> 03:34.646
Oh, well,
that can't be right.

03:34.715 --> 03:36.715
That doesn't make
any sense at all.

03:36.717 --> 03:38.116
[school bell]

03:38.252 --> 03:39.550
Oh, god.

03:41.855 --> 03:43.321
[light chatter]

03:47.695 --> 03:50.061
- I got ketchup chips.
What'd you get?

03:50.130 --> 03:51.195
- Dill pickle.

03:51.232 --> 03:52.764
- You mean
cucumber now.

03:52.800 --> 03:54.532
[chuckles]

03:54.568 --> 03:56.301
- Paula:
Attention, please!

03:56.370 --> 03:58.403
As many of you
are aware,

03:58.405 --> 04:00.438
I'm about to become
a teenager.

04:01.074 --> 04:02.474
[light applause]

04:05.212 --> 04:06.678
<i> - Paula fanning.</i>

04:06.714 --> 04:08.547
<i> Her father owned</i>
<i> two dairy queens.</i>

04:08.682 --> 04:10.349
<i> She was</i>
<i> a dairy princess</i>

04:10.484 --> 04:12.884
<i> And easily the richest girl</i>
<i> in school.</i>

04:12.953 --> 04:15.654
<i> Her father could have bought</i>
<i> all the cucumbers they wanted.</i>

04:15.656 --> 04:19.224
- To celebrate, I'm having
a birthday party this weekend.

04:19.359 --> 04:20.591
[excited reactions]

04:20.628 --> 04:22.393
My address
is in the invitation.

04:23.430 --> 04:25.229
<i> - A party</i>
<i> at paula's house!</i>

04:25.266 --> 04:28.166
<i> It was rumoured that she had</i>
<i> an indoor swimming pool.</i>

04:29.470 --> 04:31.769
<i> Not that I would ever</i>
<i> take off my shirt in public.</i>

04:36.143 --> 04:38.476
- Wow, a coupon
for a free sundae!

04:39.379 --> 04:40.912
<i> - I wanted</i>
<i> a free sundae</i>

04:41.048 --> 04:43.381
<i> But what I really wanted</i>
<i> was an invitation.</i>

04:44.584 --> 04:46.651
<i>Up to this point,</i>
<i>I had made very little impact</i>

04:46.687 --> 04:48.453
<i> On the st. Bridget's</i>
<i> social scene.</i>

04:50.457 --> 04:52.256
- You ask her.

04:52.293 --> 04:54.726
- I can't talk to
paula fanning

04:54.762 --> 04:56.327
With ketchup dust
fingers!

04:59.066 --> 05:00.498
(quietly)
- paula.

05:02.469 --> 05:03.935
Paula.

05:05.939 --> 05:07.472
(normal voice)
paula!

05:07.508 --> 05:08.907
- What?

05:10.010 --> 05:11.476
- Do we...

05:11.512 --> 05:13.144
We didn't...

05:13.180 --> 05:14.445
- Oh,

05:14.481 --> 05:16.013
You want
an invitation?

05:16.050 --> 05:17.615
[laughter]

05:17.651 --> 05:19.351
Sorry.

05:19.353 --> 05:20.652
My parents said

05:20.721 --> 05:22.420
I couldn't invite
the whole class.

05:22.456 --> 05:24.022
I'm sure
you understand.

05:24.157 --> 05:26.424
- Huh, they're the only two
not invited.

05:26.493 --> 05:29.193
- No, we're not.
Fox didn't get invited either.

05:29.229 --> 05:31.596
- What'd you say?
- Nothing.

05:31.732 --> 05:33.298
- I don't want to go
to that prissy party.

05:33.300 --> 05:35.099
- Me either.
I can't go, anyway.

05:35.135 --> 05:36.768
Me and ritchie
have plans.

05:36.804 --> 05:39.704
- Oh, really?
What's bigger than my party?

05:39.707 --> 05:42.240
- I'm sleeping over at his house
this weekend.

05:42.242 --> 05:43.909
- Yes.
Wait, what?

05:43.911 --> 05:45.510
Oh, yeah.

05:45.512 --> 05:47.712
<i> - No one had ever seen</i>
<i> where I lived before.</i>

05:47.715 --> 05:48.980
<i> I dreaded the thought.</i>

05:49.116 --> 05:50.649
<i> Surely this</i>
<i> was just talk</i>

05:50.651 --> 05:52.183
<i> And we wouldn't have to</i>
<i> go through with it!</i>

05:52.219 --> 05:53.485
- Oh, yeah?

05:53.487 --> 05:55.686
Guess I'll see you
on the bus, then.

05:55.723 --> 05:57.188
[mischievous music]

06:04.498 --> 06:06.164
- How long is this
gonna take?

06:06.299 --> 06:07.865
- I just have to interview
the first person

06:07.901 --> 06:09.267
To buy a cucumber.

06:09.269 --> 06:10.936
Now, the station really
needs this account, mary,

06:10.938 --> 06:13.805
So, please, don't talk
to me again until I'm done.

06:13.874 --> 06:15.006
- Oh, they're
never gonna sell.

06:15.008 --> 06:16.474
What are you supposed
to do with 'em?

06:16.510 --> 06:18.843
I mean, you could boil
it or something.

06:19.613 --> 06:20.946
- Attention,
shoppers.

06:21.982 --> 06:24.248
Who'd like to go live
on the radio?

06:26.220 --> 06:27.685
How are ya?

06:31.225 --> 06:33.892
Mike critch, live on the scene
at coleman's grocery

06:33.961 --> 06:35.426
In st. John's.

06:36.963 --> 06:39.164
And I'm here with
the first housewife

06:39.233 --> 06:40.499
To buy a cucumber.

06:40.634 --> 06:42.233
Congratulations,
madam.

06:42.269 --> 06:43.734
[air horn blows]

06:43.771 --> 06:45.270
[air horn
onto table]

06:45.272 --> 06:47.438
- I thought I wasn't allowed
to say anything.

06:47.474 --> 06:50.642
- Will you give this up?
I need for you to stop it!

06:50.711 --> 06:52.377
Please.

06:52.379 --> 06:53.911
- Well,

06:53.947 --> 06:56.714
I might make a nice pot
of cucumber soufflé

06:56.750 --> 06:58.784
There tonight
for my husband.

06:58.919 --> 07:00.318
See if he likes that.

07:01.788 --> 07:03.722
He's a bit of a picky arsehole,
so we'll have to wait and see.

07:03.857 --> 07:05.156
- And there
you have it.

07:05.159 --> 07:07.726
Yes, the cucumbers
are flying off the shelves

07:07.728 --> 07:09.861
Here at coleman's grocery
in st. John's.

07:09.996 --> 07:13.331
Mike critch, first on the scene
for the vocm news.

07:13.333 --> 07:14.866
-Hm.

07:14.902 --> 07:16.334
[wheels and
glass items rattle]

07:17.771 --> 07:19.404
<i> - Despite my</i>
<i> best efforts,</i>

07:19.539 --> 07:22.139
<i> It seemed ritchie</i>
<i> was sleeping over after all.</i>

07:22.176 --> 07:24.242
- Have fun on your honeymoon,
losers!

07:26.613 --> 07:28.680
- Are you sure
you want to do this?

07:28.749 --> 07:30.815
- I don't have to come over
if you don't want.

07:30.818 --> 07:32.884
I just said that to paula
to make us look good.

07:33.019 --> 07:35.019
But then I thought
it might be fun.

07:36.356 --> 07:38.089
- I should
let you know,

07:38.125 --> 07:39.590
My house is a little...

07:40.761 --> 07:42.293
Different.

07:42.329 --> 07:43.428
- Don't worry.

07:43.563 --> 07:45.363
I know your dad
is on the radio

07:45.365 --> 07:48.166
So you don't have to be
embarrassed about being rich.

07:48.301 --> 07:51.436
<i> - The 'c' in 'critch'</i>
<i> was most certainly not silent,</i>

07:51.571 --> 07:53.338
<i> As ritchie</i>
<i> was about to learn.</i>

07:53.473 --> 07:54.906
[rock music]

07:59.446 --> 08:01.012
Jazz music]

08:01.014 --> 08:02.480
[water boiling]

08:10.357 --> 08:11.822
[post lid clattering
onto pot]

08:12.659 --> 08:14.392
[heavy breathing]

08:14.428 --> 08:16.460
- Ritchie's here!
He's sleeping over!

08:16.497 --> 08:18.129
No time to explain!

08:18.131 --> 08:20.232
Please be on your
best behaviour!

08:20.367 --> 08:21.366
- That's nice.

08:21.368 --> 08:22.534
- Pop, gross!

08:22.603 --> 08:24.369
- Hey, I haven't
finished yet.

08:24.504 --> 08:26.504
One hand's
longer than the other!

08:27.107 --> 08:28.339
[knocking on door]

08:29.676 --> 08:31.543
- Please do not
embarrass me!

08:31.545 --> 08:33.010
[upbeat music]

08:34.114 --> 08:36.748
Oh, don't know how you
got locked out -- weird.

08:36.817 --> 08:39.150
Oh, well,
welcome to our house!

08:39.152 --> 08:41.887
Ritchie - everyone.
Everyone - ritchie.

08:43.490 --> 08:44.956
- Mary:
Who's that?

08:45.425 --> 08:46.857
- Ritchie.

08:47.527 --> 08:49.093
- Two beds?

08:49.129 --> 08:50.828
Cool!
Is this one mine?

08:55.168 --> 08:56.568
- Don't mind me.

08:57.771 --> 08:59.937
Just thought I'd get 40 winks
before dinner.

09:01.374 --> 09:02.774
Get off my bed,
youngster!

09:03.510 --> 09:04.976
Huss!

09:07.681 --> 09:09.314
Ohh, ah!

09:10.517 --> 09:11.983
Oh, yeah.
Nice, nice.

09:13.320 --> 09:14.986
- You sleep
with your grandfather?

09:15.589 --> 09:17.121
- No.

09:17.190 --> 09:18.990
Why would you
say that?

09:19.026 --> 09:21.326
- 'cuz he's sleeping
in your room.

09:21.395 --> 09:22.794
[snoring]

09:24.598 --> 09:26.664
- I let him sleep here
sometimes.

09:27.601 --> 09:29.634
But, trust me,
you will not notice him.

09:30.270 --> 09:31.670
- Oh!
Aww!

09:32.940 --> 09:34.405
[mumbling]

09:35.275 --> 09:36.741
[sputtering]

09:36.876 --> 09:38.543
- Wanna go see
the living room?

09:39.613 --> 09:41.279
Okay.

09:41.281 --> 09:42.814
- Ohh.

09:42.883 --> 09:44.549
Cucumbers are
getting mushy.

09:44.618 --> 09:46.217
[knocking at door]

09:46.219 --> 09:47.918
Frig sake.

09:49.890 --> 09:50.955
- Hello, ma'am.

09:50.958 --> 09:52.324
May mark come out
to play?

09:52.459 --> 09:55.059
- My god, mark's never
had this many visitors.

09:56.129 --> 09:58.363
Oh, come on in, dear,
they're in his room.

09:58.365 --> 10:00.031
- Thank you kindly,
mrs. Critch.

10:00.100 --> 10:01.633
- Mm-hm.

10:01.702 --> 10:03.101
[calm music]

10:04.204 --> 10:05.637
Just down the hall.

10:08.108 --> 10:09.707
Hm.

10:10.944 --> 10:12.343
- What's in here?

10:14.114 --> 10:15.780
Who sleeps here?

10:15.915 --> 10:17.315
- My parents.

10:18.485 --> 10:20.751
- How come they sleep
in two beds?

10:21.822 --> 10:23.588
- So, this is
your room?

10:23.590 --> 10:25.056
Kinda makes sense,
I guess.

10:25.191 --> 10:26.291
- Fox?!

10:26.426 --> 10:28.192
Don't touch that.
It's $3 a bottle!

10:28.228 --> 10:29.494
[slams bottle
onto dresser]

10:29.629 --> 10:31.862
Fox, what are you
doing here?

10:32.832 --> 10:34.732
- Got the bus driver
to let me off.

10:34.768 --> 10:37.669
Wanted to see what you freaks
were really up to.

10:37.738 --> 10:40.472
Man, this bedroom's creepy,
even for you.

10:40.607 --> 10:42.474
- This is his parents'
bedroom.

10:42.609 --> 10:45.209
Mark sleeps across the hall
with his grandfather.

10:45.245 --> 10:46.678
- So, your parents
don't bone?

10:46.680 --> 10:47.879
- You're not helping.

10:47.948 --> 10:49.347
And I don't know what
you're talking about.

10:49.482 --> 10:50.581
- Sometimes,

10:50.617 --> 10:52.616
Like on a long weekend
or dad's birthday,

10:52.653 --> 10:53.618
Parents will-

10:53.620 --> 10:55.553
- I know what she means,
ritchie!

10:55.622 --> 10:58.356
- So, then,
are you adopted or what?

11:00.460 --> 11:01.959
[electric guitar note]

11:02.029 --> 11:03.428
- Get out
of my house!

11:03.563 --> 11:05.630
- No, you get out
of your house!

11:05.632 --> 11:07.298
[grunts and groans]

11:07.300 --> 11:08.833
[mischievous music]

11:08.869 --> 11:10.301
- Give me--

11:11.705 --> 11:13.237
<i> - The government</i>
<i> didn't know</i>

11:13.273 --> 11:14.706
<i> That improperly</i>
<i> bottled cucumbers</i>

11:14.841 --> 11:16.574
<i>Sometimes explode</i>
<i>due to gas-emitting bacteria.</i>

11:16.643 --> 11:18.109
[frustrated sigh]

11:18.244 --> 11:20.445
<i> They were mass-producing</i>
<i> cucum-bombs.</i>

11:20.580 --> 11:21.679
[loud hiss]

11:21.715 --> 11:23.114
- Good news, mary!

11:23.183 --> 11:25.249
The brass at the station
gave us some cucumbers to try.

11:25.285 --> 11:27.852
We're going to be eating
like the jetsons tonight!

11:28.789 --> 11:30.421
- Get those things
out of here.

11:31.291 --> 11:32.724
<i> - Mark:</i>
<i> Help!</i>

11:34.027 --> 11:35.426
Stop!

11:35.462 --> 11:36.827
- Ow.

11:36.863 --> 11:38.796
[whining]
- mark: Stop

11:38.832 --> 11:40.198
Stop!

11:40.200 --> 11:42.400
- I didn't know
the boy had it in him.

11:42.535 --> 11:43.667
- She's an intruder!

11:43.704 --> 11:45.870
- You have a lovely bedroom,
mrs. Critch.

11:46.005 --> 11:47.639
- Lovely of you
to say.

11:48.742 --> 11:49.808
Would you like to
stay for supper, dear?

11:49.943 --> 11:51.509
- Why, yes,
please.

11:51.545 --> 11:53.811
I'll call mom
to come get me later.

11:53.880 --> 11:56.214
- What do you kids
think about cucumbers?

11:56.349 --> 11:58.550
- They're okay, I guess.
- Oh, they're lovely.

11:59.319 --> 12:00.918
- Good.

12:00.920 --> 12:02.353
Good.

12:05.225 --> 12:06.891
[foreboding
music]

12:07.026 --> 12:10.094
<i>- When word got out,</i>
<i>my social life would be over.</i>

12:10.163 --> 12:12.196
<i> That is, if I survived</i>
<i> the weekend.</i>

12:14.234 --> 12:16.100
- Here come
the boiled cucumbers.

12:16.103 --> 12:17.502
[gasp]
and gravy.

12:17.637 --> 12:19.237
- Pop:
Oh, hm.

12:19.239 --> 12:21.306
<i> - Company meant we used</i>
<i> the dining room,</i>

12:21.441 --> 12:23.575
<i> Usually saved for</i>
<i> special occasions.</i>

12:24.478 --> 12:26.711
- Mary: Oh, look,
another card.

12:26.713 --> 12:28.379
Let's see
who it's from.

12:28.448 --> 12:30.581
Happy birthday
from randall insurance.

12:30.617 --> 12:32.450
- Tom mcadam
or jeff peddle?

12:32.452 --> 12:34.385
- Ah, both.
[laughs]

12:34.387 --> 12:35.720
Blow out
your candles.

12:35.789 --> 12:38.189
♪♪ happy birthday to--

12:38.258 --> 12:39.924
- I must say,
mrs. Critch,

12:39.960 --> 12:41.826
I've never had
hot cucumber before.

12:41.862 --> 12:44.462
- I'll have to get the recipe.
- Oh.

12:44.531 --> 12:47.064
Well, it's not the first time
we've had cucumbers, of course.

12:47.134 --> 12:48.466
We often have them,
don't you know?

12:48.535 --> 12:51.069
- Am I supposed to eat it
or-or drink it?

12:51.071 --> 12:53.471
- Good god,
there's no taste to it at all.

12:53.473 --> 12:54.872
- You hate flavour.

12:55.008 --> 12:56.908
- I need a tums now.

12:56.910 --> 12:58.342
Too much
exotic food!

12:58.378 --> 13:00.077
- Mary:
Try one with gravy.

13:01.148 --> 13:03.113
- Where's he gonna sleep,
my bed?

13:03.150 --> 13:05.216
Oh, I-I can do the math.

13:05.285 --> 13:07.819
I suppose it's the home
for me, then, is it?

13:07.821 --> 13:10.621
Drop me off at the harbour,
why don't ya?

13:10.657 --> 13:12.257
Just put me out
on an ice floe!

13:12.259 --> 13:14.425
- Next time someone mentions
a g.D. Cucumber,

13:14.494 --> 13:16.227
I'm gonna shove one
up their arse!

13:16.263 --> 13:17.928
- Cucumber, cucumber,
cucumber!

13:18.698 --> 13:20.231
[exasperated
exclamation]

13:20.267 --> 13:21.699
What?

13:21.768 --> 13:23.301
Do you want
my grave next?

13:23.436 --> 13:24.969
Is that it?

13:24.971 --> 13:26.437
[gloomy music]

13:34.447 --> 13:36.914
- Aren't we supposed to
tell secrets at sleepovers?

13:38.118 --> 13:39.584
- Pop:
You first.

13:39.653 --> 13:41.118
Was that
your girlfriend?

13:41.188 --> 13:42.319
- No.

13:42.355 --> 13:43.654
She's his bully.

13:43.690 --> 13:44.789
- Shut up!

13:44.858 --> 13:46.991
Fox is gonna tell everyone
I'm a weirdo.

13:46.993 --> 13:48.660
Why else would she
come here?

13:48.795 --> 13:51.195
- People do stupid stuff
when they're lonely.

13:52.299 --> 13:54.265
- Well, that is some
boring gossip.

13:54.400 --> 13:55.934
I'm going to bed.

13:58.805 --> 14:00.271
[groaning]

14:01.674 --> 14:03.107
[sighs]

14:03.143 --> 14:04.542
- Why is
the room glowing?

14:04.677 --> 14:07.211
- That's just the light
from the sprung greenhouse.

14:07.280 --> 14:09.047
You can see it
from space.

14:09.182 --> 14:10.715
<i> - The sprung greenhouse</i>

14:10.850 --> 14:12.884
<i> Was located on the</i>
<i> outskirts of town</i>

14:13.019 --> 14:15.520
<i> Which meant that my room</i>
<i> was bathed nightly</i>

14:15.522 --> 14:17.822
<i> In the amber</i>
<i> hydroponic glow</i>

14:17.824 --> 14:20.124
<i> Of the mad scientist's</i>
<i> cucumber factory.</i>

14:21.027 --> 14:22.760
- I don't even
notice it anymore.

14:23.363 --> 14:24.629
[pop coughing]

14:25.999 --> 14:27.464
[coughing
continues]

14:29.302 --> 14:30.868
[groaning]

14:30.871 --> 14:32.303
<i> - Mike sr.:</i>
<i> Hold still.</i>

14:33.807 --> 14:35.039
<i>I can't get the calamine lotion</i>
<i>on your burns if you're moving.</i>

14:35.041 --> 14:37.441
<i>- Mary: Ow, mike, you got hands</i>
<i>like a bloody gorilla!</i>

14:37.477 --> 14:38.976
<i> - It's from typing!</i>

14:39.045 --> 14:40.445
<i> - That stings.</i>

14:41.047 --> 14:42.647
- Hey...

14:42.649 --> 14:45.282
Maybe we can sleep over
at my house tomorrow?

14:46.653 --> 14:48.052
- Yeah.

14:48.187 --> 14:49.620
That might be nice.

14:50.523 --> 14:51.656
<i> - Mike sr.:</i>
<i> Stop squirming.</i>

14:51.658 --> 14:53.725
<i> Maybe try some</i>
<i> margarine on it.</i>

14:53.727 --> 14:55.192
[pop groaning loudly]

14:59.599 --> 15:00.998
Big band music]

15:04.737 --> 15:06.704
- Oh, got too much
too much.

15:08.074 --> 15:10.942
- And how long
are you going for, a month?

15:10.944 --> 15:12.977
- You think
I packed too much?

15:12.979 --> 15:16.347
- Not unless you're planning
on beating peary to the pole.

15:16.383 --> 15:18.082
Here, let me
have a look.

15:18.118 --> 15:21.886
Maybe there's a couple of things
in here you could do without.

15:22.021 --> 15:23.487
Oh!

15:23.556 --> 15:25.156
1939

15:25.158 --> 15:27.425
King george
commemorative mug?

15:27.494 --> 15:29.160
- I like a cup of tea
before bed.

15:29.295 --> 15:30.761
1- okay, well...

15:31.631 --> 15:33.263
Two pairs of pajamas?

15:33.300 --> 15:34.632
- That set
is flannel.

15:34.767 --> 15:37.168
I don't know how cold
he keeps his room.

15:37.237 --> 15:38.769
- Oh, potted meat,

15:38.838 --> 15:40.238
Noxzema.

15:41.441 --> 15:42.907
A loaf of bread.

15:43.042 --> 15:44.508
[crinkling]

15:45.912 --> 15:47.378
Toilet paper.

15:47.948 --> 15:49.380
Mark,

15:49.449 --> 15:51.382
You don't need
any of this stuff.

15:52.519 --> 15:54.785
- I've never been invited
to a sleepover before.

15:56.055 --> 15:58.088
- You don't have to
be worried.

15:59.058 --> 16:00.858
Listen, all families
are different

16:00.927 --> 16:02.126
And yet,

16:02.128 --> 16:04.094
All families
are the same.

16:05.198 --> 16:07.198
You know, there's things
you don't like about his

16:07.200 --> 16:10.434
And things that he probably
doesn't like about here.

16:11.070 --> 16:12.569
But all I do know,

16:12.605 --> 16:15.005
With all this stuff,
you'll look like a fool.

16:16.009 --> 16:17.608
And you don't need
any help doing that

16:17.644 --> 16:20.945
Because your parents have you
well covered in that department.

16:20.947 --> 16:23.348
[tender music]
[both chuckle]

16:23.483 --> 16:25.682
<i> - Ritchie's house</i>
<i> was a suburban dream.</i>

16:25.719 --> 16:28.285
<i> A vinyl siding wrapped</i>
<i> bungalow</i>

16:28.321 --> 16:31.222
<i>With fancy steps</i>
<i>and a postage stamp-sized yard.</i>

16:33.560 --> 16:35.960
- You have a second
living room downstairs?

16:36.029 --> 16:37.962
- Sorry, it's
our lame rec room.

16:38.097 --> 16:40.498
<i> - I had never heard</i>
<i> of a rec room before.</i>

16:40.500 --> 16:41.932
- But we can watch
movie channel,

16:42.002 --> 16:43.701
Play atari.
You like pitfall?

16:43.836 --> 16:45.803
We have the
commodore 64 too.

16:45.938 --> 16:49.840
<i>- It was at that exact moment</i>
<i> that I realized I was poor.</i>

16:49.876 --> 16:51.909
- Do your parents
sleep in the same bed?

16:51.911 --> 16:53.344
- Yeah, they have
a waterbed.

16:53.413 --> 16:54.746
But I have two beds
in my room.

16:54.881 --> 16:56.547
Well, it's a bunk bed
but still...

16:57.250 --> 16:58.715
- Oh.

16:59.319 --> 17:00.918
You must think

17:00.920 --> 17:02.453
I'm pretty weird, huh?

17:02.522 --> 17:04.121
- No, your house is...

17:04.591 --> 17:06.156
Different,

17:06.192 --> 17:07.792
Like, but really cool.

17:07.927 --> 17:10.060
I never saw someone
shine shoes before.

17:10.997 --> 17:12.529
- Yeah, but
you've got everything.

17:12.565 --> 17:14.331
- But what good is that
if I don't have anyone

17:14.401 --> 17:15.933
To use it with?

17:16.002 --> 17:17.402
- Hello.

17:19.739 --> 17:21.338
You must be mark.

17:21.374 --> 17:23.474
I'm so happy
ritchie has a friend!

17:23.543 --> 17:25.610
I brought you boys
some snacks.

17:25.745 --> 17:28.479
Your father and I are going out
to a dinner tonight.

17:28.614 --> 17:30.414
I left the phone number
on the wall.

17:30.417 --> 17:32.349
So good meeting you, mark.

17:32.385 --> 17:34.418
- A pleasure.
- Um-hm.

17:34.421 --> 17:35.820
- Thanks, mom.

17:36.823 --> 17:38.156
- They leave you alone?
[doorbell]

17:38.291 --> 17:39.690
Cool.

17:39.759 --> 17:42.226
- They work a lot at the
hospital but I'm used to it.

17:42.262 --> 17:43.361
- My parents
never go out.

17:43.496 --> 17:44.762
There's always
somebody home.

17:44.764 --> 17:45.963
- Lucky.

17:46.699 --> 17:47.965
- Ritchie,

17:48.034 --> 17:49.700
You have
another friend here!

17:49.769 --> 17:51.302
She's very pretty.

17:51.371 --> 17:53.237
- Why, thank you,
mrs. Perez.

17:53.239 --> 17:55.306
- What a lovely home you have.
- Oh.

17:55.375 --> 17:56.874
<i> - Fox was like dracula.</i>

17:56.910 --> 17:59.043
<i> She couldn't enter your home</i>
<i> unless she was invited in.</i>

17:59.112 --> 18:00.844
<i> But once she</i>
<i> crossed your threshold,</i>

18:00.880 --> 18:02.647
<i> You were as good</i>
<i> as dead.</i>

18:02.782 --> 18:03.714
- Nice pad, perez.

18:03.850 --> 18:05.650
Better than that dick's
cocoon house.

18:05.652 --> 18:07.985
- Uh, what are you
doing here?

18:07.987 --> 18:09.720
- I've come to get you
for paula's party.

18:09.722 --> 18:11.656
- We weren't invited.

18:11.658 --> 18:13.591
- That's exactly
why we're going.

18:13.593 --> 18:14.725
She didn't invite us,

18:14.761 --> 18:16.527
So we're going to go there
and wreck it.

18:16.662 --> 18:17.928
Look!

18:17.997 --> 18:20.131
We take these and throw them
at the house.

18:20.133 --> 18:21.532
Cover it
in squished cucumber.

18:21.667 --> 18:24.134
- Cucumbers are hard.
They won't squish.

18:25.171 --> 18:26.737
- God, you're so lame!

18:26.773 --> 18:29.340
- If we're so lame, then
how come you keep following us?

18:29.475 --> 18:30.908
- I'm not following you!

18:30.977 --> 18:33.010
- You don't have to make up
a reason to come over.

18:33.012 --> 18:34.145
- Trust me,

18:34.280 --> 18:36.681
I don't want to stay here
with you geeks!

18:37.417 --> 18:38.716
Fine.

18:38.785 --> 18:39.984
If you guys
don't want to help me,

18:40.119 --> 18:41.585
I'll just do it myself.

18:41.654 --> 18:43.754
<i> - I realized then,</i>
<i> for the first time,</i>

18:43.823 --> 18:45.823
<i> That fox didn't</i>
<i> want to bully us.</i>

18:45.825 --> 18:47.091
<i> She wanted to be</i>
<i> our friend.</i>

18:47.226 --> 18:48.926
<i> She just</i>
<i> didn't know how.</i>

18:49.496 --> 18:50.961
- Fox, uh...

18:51.030 --> 18:52.630
Why don't
you stay?

18:52.632 --> 18:54.332
Three people
can play this one.

19:00.340 --> 19:01.772
- Screw off.

19:03.309 --> 19:04.909
[melancholy music
and woman vocalizing]

19:06.379 --> 19:07.844
[video game
sound effects]

19:09.616 --> 19:11.081
- Mark:
So...

19:21.895 --> 19:24.462
<i> - Home's a place</i>
<i> you grow up wanting to leave</i>

19:24.597 --> 19:26.930
<i> And grow old</i>
<i> wanting to come back to.</i>

19:28.000 --> 19:29.700
<i> Ritchie had everything</i>
<i> I ever wanted.</i>

19:30.970 --> 19:32.336
<i> But as I</i>
<i> lay there,</i>

19:32.405 --> 19:34.471
<i> In a different room</i>
<i> in a new house,</i>

19:34.473 --> 19:35.673
<i> All I wanted</i>

19:35.675 --> 19:37.341
<i> Was to hear</i>
<i> pop snoring.</i>

19:37.377 --> 19:38.842
[tender music]

19:40.647 --> 19:42.646
- If cucumbers
are the future,

19:43.616 --> 19:46.083
We really are in
one helluva...

19:46.152 --> 19:47.585
Pickle.

19:50.490 --> 19:53.023
Those cucumbers really did
wonders for your skin.

19:53.760 --> 19:55.259
You look
just like a...

19:55.394 --> 19:56.994
Hollywood actress.

20:00.867 --> 20:02.567
<i> - As small</i>
<i> as a home is,</i>

20:02.702 --> 20:05.302
<i> It's never small enough</i>
<i> to keep the people you love</i>

20:05.338 --> 20:06.803
<i> Close to you.</i>

20:08.408 --> 20:10.007
[doorbell]

20:10.009 --> 20:11.442
[excited
conversations]

20:11.577 --> 20:12.977
<i> - Girl:</i>
<i> Stop!</i>

20:15.181 --> 20:18.115
<i> - Sometimes, the biggest</i>
<i> of houses can feel empty</i>

20:18.251 --> 20:19.683
<i> Even when</i>
<i> it's filled.</i>

20:27.793 --> 20:29.393
[loud hiss]
[scream]

20:29.395 --> 20:30.927
<i> - Paula:</i>
<i> Gross!</i>

20:30.964 --> 20:32.997
<i> - And, sometimes,</i>
<i> people are most at home</i>

20:33.132 --> 20:34.564
<i> All on their own.</i>

20:36.869 --> 20:37.935
- Woo-hoo!

20:38.070 --> 20:39.603
[emotional music
continues]

20:39.606 --> 20:40.938
<i> - Tv reporter:</i>
<i> This just in:</i>

20:41.073 --> 20:42.440
<i> The sprung greenhouse,</i>

20:42.575 --> 20:45.676
<i> Built at a cost to taxpayers</i>
<i> of $22 million,</i>

20:45.712 --> 20:47.811
<i> Has closed</i>
<i> just months after it opened.</i>

20:47.880 --> 20:50.447
<i> Thousands of cucumbers</i>
<i> remain unsold.</i>

20:50.483 --> 20:53.150
<i> Area grocers are offering them</i>
<i> for free to farmers</i>

20:53.219 --> 20:54.951
<i> To feed their cows.</i>

20:54.988 --> 20:56.554
- Thank christ
that's over.

20:56.556 --> 20:58.955
Mary, do we have
any cans of corned beef?

21:00.092 --> 21:02.559
<i> - I guess what really</i>
<i> makes a house a home</i>

21:02.629 --> 21:05.262
<i> Is knowing you can</i>
<i> always come back to it.</i>

21:07.700 --> 21:09.633
<i> And that someone</i>
<i> is waiting for you</i>

21:09.636 --> 21:11.101
<i> When you do.</i>

21:11.971 --> 21:13.437
<i> ♪♪ home</i>

21:23.116 --> 21:24.581
[upbeat jazz music]
